        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Extended Description</title>
            <para>The service brake circuit function is to signal the ECM when the brake pedal is applied. This
                information is used to disengage the Cruise Control and PTO functions. This signal is also used for ECM
                control of the Vehicle Retarder and exhaust brake enabling. The brake signal will interrupt the Cold
                Ambient Protection feature and will reset the time interval for the Idle Shut Down feature.
            </para>
            <para>Four systems are used for the service brake signal:</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Hydraulic Brakes</title>
            <para>See Hydraulic Brake System Circuit Diagram
                <hotlnk xrefid="f17503026">
                    <xref refid="f17503026"/>
                </hotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>Hydraulic brakes use single throw switch (double pole). The throw switch is a self adjusting, mounted
                at the brake pedal. When the brake pedal is not applied, the brake pedal holds the switch in the open
                state. Current is supplied by fuse F9 to the primary side of the switch and fuse F33 to the secondary
                side of the switch. Applying the brakes closes the switch to supply current to circuits 97M and 70C.
            </para>
            <para>Circuit 70C supplies voltage to:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Operate the turn signal switch relay for brake light operation.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Circuit 97N to signal the ECM at terminal 43 to indicate the brakes have been applied.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para>Circuit 97M supplies voltage to the brake module and to the ECM at terminal 44 as a redundant signal
                to verify brake application.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Service Brake Switches</title>
            <para>See Stoplight Switch (with air brake), 3000FE Chassis, Built January 11, 1999 and After
                <hotlnk xrefid="f17503030">
                    <xref refid="f17503030"/>
                </hotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>the appropriate circuit diagram for the following discussion:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With tractor air brakes a single normally open switch is used. Air pressure closes the
                    switch with brakes applied.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With air brakes two normally open air operated switches are in parallel circuits.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With hydraulic brakes two mechanical switches are used, but only one of the switches is
                    linked to the ECM. The switches are activated by the brake pedal arm.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para id="f175fc222">
                <emph type="bold">Diagnostic Trouble Code 222</emph>
                <emph type="bold">SID 247 FMI 2</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Brake Switch Circuit Diagnostic Trouble Code</emph>
            </para>
            <para>The ECM continuously monitors terminals 43 and 44 for voltage. If voltage is at one of the terminals
                and not the other, the ECM will set Diagnostic Trouble Code 222.
            </para>
            <para>When Diagnostic Trouble Code 222 is
                <emph type="bold">active</emph>, all features using brake signal inputs will be disabled. Diagnostic
                Trouble Code 222 will not cause the Warn Engine Light to illuminate.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Possible Causes:</emph>If a defective fuse, switch, or an open wire causes an open
                circuit, voltage may not be present at terminal 43 or 44.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Before Troubleshooting</title>
            <para>Before troubleshooting, make sure the batteries are fully charged. Voltage readings will not be
                accurate if the batteries are not fully charged
            </para>
            <para>Check battery cables and grounds for clean, tight connections free of damage.</para>
            <para>Inspect circuit connectors for pushed back, loose or damaged (spread or bent) terminals, and wires
                with cut strands. Wires and connections must be free of damage or corrosion. When some connectors
                corrode, a light white residue will be present that must be removed.
            </para>
            <para>Inspect the suspect ground circuit for clean, tight connections free of damage.</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Troubleshooting</title>
            <para>The Electronic Service Tool (EST) can retrieve a Diagnostic Trouble Code set in the ECM. The EST can
                also clear Diagnostic Trouble Codes once the problem is resolved.
            </para>
            <para>To determine the operation of the brake switch circuit, monitor the EST data list to display brake
                status.
            </para>
